secretary said 20
years of attempts to curb
Pyongyang's nuclear

11:53.346 --> 11:55.281 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ambitions have failed.

11:55.315 --> 11:58.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REX TILLERSON: In the face of
this ever-escalating
threat, it is clear that a
different approach

11:58.851 --> 12:00.687 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is required.

12:00.720 --> 12:06.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The purpose of -- part of the
purpose of my
visit to the region is to
exchange views on

12:06.426 --> 12:07.894 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a new approach.

12:07.927 --> 12:10.330 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This morning,
President
Trump weighed in via Twitter.

12:10.363 --> 12:13.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He wrote: "North Korea is
behaving very badly.

12:13.733 --> 12:16.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have been playing the
United States for
years.

12:16.769 --> 12:18.905 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
China has done little to help."

12:18.938 --> 12:23.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Chinese have condemned North
Korea's nuclear
and missile tests.

12:23.109 --> 12:27.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they also oppose deployment
of the U.S.
ballistic missile defense
system, known as

12:27.780 --> 12:29.582 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
THAAD, to South Korea.

12:29.616 --> 12:32.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tillerson answered today in
Seoul, before
heading to Beijing tomorrow.

12:32.585 --> 12:37.156 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
REX TILLERSON: While we
acknowledge China's
opposition, its economic
retaliation against

12:37.190 --> 12:40.927 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
South Korea is inappropriate and
troubling.

12:40.960 --> 12:43.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We ask China to refrain from
such action.

12:43.429 --> 12:47.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The South
Korean foreign
minister underscored the U.S.
argument that

12:47.500 --> 12:51.237 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the missile defense system is
not aimed at
China.

12:51.270 --> 12:55.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the recent ouster of South
Korea's president,
in a corruption scandal, could
change the

12:55.775 --> 12:57.744 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
landscape.

12:57.777 --> 13:01.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The liberal candidate favored to
win the presidency
in May says he will review the
THAAD deployment,

13:01.748 --> 13:03.916 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and consult with China.

13:03.950 --> 13:07.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on the secretary's trip
to Asia,
and the significance of what
Tillerson had

13:07.987 --> 13:11.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to say in South Korea, we turn
to veteran
diplomat Kathleen Stephens.

13:12.025 --> 13:15.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was U.S. ambassador to South
Korea during
the Obama administration.

13:15.728 --> 13:17.964 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She's now at Stanford
University.

13:17.997 --> 13:20.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How significant were the
secretary's remarks?

13:20.099 --> 13:24.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATHLEEN STEPHENS, Former U.S.
Ambassador
to South Korea: Well, I think
they were very

13:24.070 --> 13:27.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
significant, and closely
listened to and heard
throughout the region, as well
as here.

13:27.907 --> 13:33.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, I think it's first
somewhat extensive
press conferences as secretary
of state.

13:33.479 --> 13:37.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was indeed a very tough
message, but I
also think he picked his words
pretty carefully.

13:37.750 --> 13:43.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a lot of what he had to say
was a reinforcement
of what had been the Obama
administration

13:43.790 --> 13:46.959 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
policy, but I think an
indication that he
wants to toughen it up even
more.

13:46.993 --> 13:50.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is this our
chief diplomat
saying diplomacy hasn't been
working, the

13:50.730 --> 13:52.565 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
talking hasn't been working?

13:52.598 --> 13:57.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATHLEEN STEPHENS: Well, in
fact, there hasn't
been much talking with North
Korea over the

13:57.937 --> 13:59.706 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
eight years.

13:59.739 --> 14:06.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one thing that did strike me
about Secretary
Tillerson's remarks was that he
was quite

14:06.446 --> 14:10.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
specific and categorical in
saying now is
not the time for talks.

14:10.450 --> 14:16.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I actually would have liked to
have seen him
keep the door a little bit ajar
on that, because

14:16.222 --> 14:20.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, when you do have a new
administration
in Washington, there will soon
be a new administration

14:21.027 --> 14:26.099 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in Seoul, there's a good
argument for trying
to climb that mountain one more
time and seeing

14:26.132 --> 14:30.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what's possible diplomatically,
because at
the very least, it helps you
build coalitions

14:30.336 --> 14:33.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
you need to increase the
pressure if the diplomatic
approach doesn't work.

14:33.840 --> 14:36.209 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: He's
advocating tougher
sanctions.

14:36.242 --> 14:38.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Will tougher sanctions work
against North
Korea?

14:38.878 --> 14:42.849 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
KATHLEEN STEPHENS: Well,
sanctions are a very
blunt instrument.

14:42.882 --> 14:48.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And sanctions have been --
against North Korea
have been progressively
tightened and broadened

14:48.621 --> 14:54.627 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
through Security Council
resolutions, through
bilateral action by the United
States, by

14:54.660 --> 14:57.630 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
actions by South Korea and
Japan.

14:57.663 --> 15:03.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
China has also participated,
although, of
course, there's never been
satisfaction, I

15:03.336 --> 15:09.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think, with China doing or a
sense that China
is doing as much as it possibly
could.

15:09.475 --> 15:11.010 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But will sanctions work?

15:11.043 --> 15:14.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think they can bring pressure
on the regime,
and they are bringing pressure.

15:14.480 --> 15:20.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Will they lead Kim Jong-un to
make a strategic
choice that he's ready to trade
his nuclear

15:20.253 --> 15:25.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and missile program for a
lessening of sanctions
and for other benefits?

15:25.691 --> 15:31.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that the chances of that
working are
far less promising perhaps than
they ever

15:31.531 --> 15:32.498 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
have been.

15:32.532 --> 15:34.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it doesn't mean you give up
on sanctions.

15:34.300 --> 15:36.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think it means it has to
be only one
part of your approach.

15:36.936 --> 15:41.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Given what we
know and we
don't know about North Korea's
leader, is

15:41.040 --> 15:45.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this the type of thing that
prods him to come
to the table, or does it just
anger him more?

15:45.645 --> 15:48.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, at times, his actions have
not been predictable.

15:48.381 --> 15:53.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATHLEEN STEPHENS: Well, I think
what we know
about Kim Jong-un, who has now
been in power

15:53.119 --> 15:59.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for five years, is that a
priority, his priority
has been to accelerate and
consolidate his

15:59.192 --> 16:01.327 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
nuclear weapon and ballistic
missile capability.

16:01.360 --> 16:08.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to date, the sanctions, the
isolation,
the -- and, for that matter, the
carrots that

16:08.201 --> 16:11.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have been offered to him to do
otherwise have
not been sufficient.

16:11.037 --> 16:13.439 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, I am pessimistic about them.

16:13.472 --> 16:20.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think that continued
pressure is important,
because you don't know what the
timeline is

16:20.046 --> 16:21.981 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for getting somebody to the
table.

16:22.014 --> 16:24.150 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think Secretary Tillerson
is right.

16:24.183 --> 16:31.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Indeed, it was something that
the Obama administration
emphasized, that China also
plays a very important

16:31.324 --> 16:32.692 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
role.

16:32.725 --> 16:35.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think sanctions have to be
combined
with some kind of exit ramp.

16:35.528 --> 16:42.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the ramp has to be into
something that
allows him to start to make some
adjustments.

16:42.134 --> 16:46.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And given where he is in the
program, we may
have to lower our sights about
what he needs

16:46.739 --> 16:48.241 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to do to get into talks.

16:48.274 --> 16:52.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this was one part of Mr.
Tillerson's presentation
that concerned me a bit.

16:52.612 --> 16:57.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He stated, perhaps for tactical
reasons, a
kind of a maximalist approach,
which has long

16:57.216 --> 17:00.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been an approach which has --
that basically
North Korea needs to give up
everything before

17:00.987 --> 17:02.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
we get into a diplomatic
process.

17:02.955 --> 17:09.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do think it is going to have
to be a process,
probably a slow process, but
certainly the

17:09.328 --> 17:13.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
principle which was held by
Obama administration,
which Mr. Tillerson reinforced,
that there

17:13.866 --> 17:18.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
needs to be a readiness on the
part of North
Korea to say they are prepared
to move toward

17:18.271 --> 17:20.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
denuclearization, is an
important prerequisite.

17:20.072 --> 17:24.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that is one that the Chinese
have also
agreed to and need to reinforce.

17:24.076 --> 17:28.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Something that
has been
of interest in South Korea is
not who Mr.

17:28.347 --> 17:30.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tillerson met with, but who he
didn't meet
with.

17:30.316 --> 17:32.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He didn't seem to meet with any
of the opposition
leaders.

17:32.818 --> 17:35.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he kind of talked to an
administration
that is a lame-duck.

17:35.788 --> 17:40.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How significant are things -- or
how much
is it likely to change after
South Korea has

17:40.493 --> 17:41.527 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a new election?

17:41.560 --> 17:43.329 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KATHLEEN STEPHENS: Right.

17:43.362 --> 17:48.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's always a tricky question in
the middle
of an election campaign is how
you can manage

17:48.067 --> 17:49.602 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
those meetings.

17:49.635 --> 17:54.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I have some sympathy with
the diplomatic
nuances of trying to do that.

17:54.240 --> 17:59.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, certainly, I mean, less
than two months'
time, South Korea will have a
new president.

17:59.412 --> 18:00.646 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The election is on May 9.

18:00.680 --> 18:04.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that new president will take
power, I
guess, immediately.

18:04.784 --> 18:11.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it looks now that it's going
to be most
likely a president from the part
of the political

18:11.557 --> 18:15.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
spectrum that has tended to lean
towards trying
a little harder on the
engagement angle with

18:16.028 --> 18:17.763 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
North Korea.

18:17.797 --> 18:21.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In any event, I think any new
South Korean
will want to look at the options
for that.

18:21.534 --> 18:26.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think it will be very
important not
to close off too many options
before that

18:26.872 --> 18:32.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
new government gets in place,
and then to
see with Seoul, as well as with
Beijing, what,

18:32.078 --> 18:37.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
along with deepened pressure,
deepened sanctions,
more countries participating and
pressuring

18:37.750 --> 18:44.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
North Korea, what might be
possible in terms
of a fresh diplomatic approach,
some kind

18:44.056 --> 18:50.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of grand bargain that addresses
our core interest
in seeing all of the Korean
Peninsula denuclearize

18:50.763 --> 18:56.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- and that means no nuclear
weapons in North
Korea -- but finds a way to get
into some

18:56.168 --> 18:57.470 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
kind of talks on that basis.

18:57.503 --> 18:58.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Kathleen Stephens,
thanks so much.

18:58.771 --> 19:07.813 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KATHLEEN STEPHENS: My pleasure.

19:07.847 --> 19:16.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: President Trump
and the Republican
leadership in the House are
working to pass

19:16.889 --> 19:19.492 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
