that subsidy
would be $4,000 flat, across the
board.

20:48.280 --> 20:49.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't know where you live.

20:49.782 --> 20:53.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is virtually impossible to
purchase insurance
at that age for $4,000.

20:54.019 --> 20:56.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Do you see an
impact on your
own patients?

20:56.689 --> 20:58.390 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You're already hearing the
worries?

20:58.424 --> 21:00.159 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

21:00.192 --> 21:02.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW GURMAN: The worries that
my patients
have, have to do with high
deductibles and

21:02.628 --> 21:04.463 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
availability of insurance.

21:04.497 --> 21:09.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I can give you example of
someone I saw
last week in my office,
self-employed carpenter,

21:09.835 --> 21:13.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
probably makes somewhere between
$20,000 and
$30,000 in a good year.

21:13.672 --> 21:15.241 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He needs to have surgery on his
hand.

21:15.274 --> 21:16.675 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He has a $6,000 deductible.

21:16.709 --> 21:18.511 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's a big problem for him.

21:18.544 --> 21:21.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, to push back
a little bit
on you here, many doctors have
also, of course,

21:21.647 --> 21:26.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
complained about the ACA, right,
about the
-- too many regulations, gets in
the way of

21:26.919 --> 21:31.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the doctor-patient relationship,
takes away
choices from patients.

21:31.056 --> 21:35.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You are also getting some
pushback from the
White House about that you and
other interest

21:35.261 --> 21:40.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
groups are opposed because it
hits you financially,
you doctors financially.

21:40.699 --> 21:41.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What do you respond?

21:41.700 --> 21:43.369 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

21:43.402 --> 21:45.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW GURMAN: Well, there is no
question
that there are things in the
Affordable Care

21:45.037 --> 21:47.740 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Act that need to be fixed.

21:47.773 --> 21:50.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are various ways that that
could be
done.

21:50.276 --> 21:53.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Repeal and replace is one of
them, but we
don't know what the replacement
is.

21:53.646 --> 21:59.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the AMA has clearly stated
that we think
that the American people should
see what the

21:59.151 --> 22:03.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
proposed replacement is, so that
we can have
a thoughtful discussion
regarding whether

22:03.722 --> 22:05.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it's better or worse than what
we have now.

22:05.958 --> 22:10.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are many things in the
Affordable Care
Act that could be fixed, rather
than replaced.

22:10.429 --> 22:15.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The repeated
claim behind all
this, of course, is that
Obamacare is collapsing.

22:15.834 --> 22:16.769 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Do you see that?

22:16.802 --> 22:18.737 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

22:18.771 --> 22:21.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW GURMAN: Well, there's no
question that
the markets which were created
under the Affordable

22:21.440 --> 22:22.741 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Care Act need to be stabilized.

22:22.775 --> 22:24.476 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There are lots of ways to do
that.

22:24.510 --> 22:27.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, finally, the
president
says we're going to get through
all this,

22:27.746 --> 22:30.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we're going to get a new health
plan.

22:30.583 --> 22:32.418 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Do you think that will happen?

22:32.451 --> 22:34.620 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What will it take to get the AMA
on board?

22:34.653 --> 22:36.422 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

22:36.455 --> 22:40.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW GURMAN: Well, the AMA
stands ready,
willing and eager to work with
Congress in

22:40.626 --> 22:43.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
order to get this right and to
make it work
for all Americans.

22:43.462 --> 22:45.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, again, do
you think it
will happen?

22:45.798 --> 22:46.765 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

22:46.799 --> 22:48.534 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANDREW GURMAN: I hope so.

22:48.567 --> 22:49.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You do hope so,
even though
you oppose what is on the table
right now?

22:49.702 --> 22:51.437 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

22:51.470 --> 22:52.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW GURMAN: Oh, I hope that,
at the end
of this process, that we have a
health care

22:52.871 --> 22:55.641 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
system that works for everybody
in America.

22:55.674 --> 22:56.642 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right.

22:56.675 --> 22:57.776 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

22:57.810 --> 22:58.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANDREW GURMAN: It's already the
envy of the
world.

22:58.677 --> 23:00.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We just need to make it work for
us.

23:00.112 --> 23:04.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Dr. Andrew
Gurman, president
of the AMA, thank you.

23:04.650 --> 23:05.618 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

23:05.651 --> 23:09.555 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANDREW GURMAN: My pleasure.

23:09.588 --> 23:14.460 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you for having me.

23:14.493 --> 23:18.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And to the
analysis of Shields
and Brooks.

23:18.831 --> 23:23.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's syndicated columnist Mark
Shields and
New York Times columnist David
Brooks.

23:23.068 --> 23:24.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome, gentleman.

23:24.937 --> 23:29.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, let's pick up with the
conversation, David,
that Jeffrey Brown was just
having with the

23:29.375 --> 23:32.177 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
head of the American Medical
Association.

23:32.211 --> 23:37.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump is saying again
today the
health care overhaul is moving
along very

23:37.549 --> 23:40.152 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
well, it's going to move through
the House.

23:40.185 --> 23:41.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What do you see as the
prospects?

23:41.186 --> 23:42.521 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: It has no critics.

23:42.554 --> 23:43.522 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
No.

23:43.555 --> 23:46.392 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm first all amazed that they
did it first.

23:46.425 --> 23:50.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of all the issues to tackle,
health scare
is probably the hardest one.

23:50.396 --> 23:55.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so every four or eight
years, some president
decides, you know, let's do
health care first.

23:55.167 --> 23:57.603 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it hurts them every single
time.

23:57.636 --> 24:01.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Whether the prospects of this
bill are good,
I tend to doubt.

24:01.907 --> 24:04.576 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It has very few fans in the
Senate.

24:04.610 --> 24:08.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And it has two wings of
opposition which are
in contradiction, what we call
the coverage

24:08.681 --> 24:12.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
caucus, who want a little more
expensive bill
that will cover more people, and
the Freedom

24:12.284 --> 24:15.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Caucus wants a less expensive
bill to cover
less.

24:15.154 --> 24:17.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can't -- they have to win
both of these
groups.

24:17.389 --> 24:19.925 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And how do you do this, when
they are mutually
contradictory?

24:19.958 --> 24:21.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so the Senate is very
daunting.

24:21.760 --> 24:25.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, therefore, you're asking the
House members
to vote for something that will
take away

24:25.864 --> 24:31.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coverage that already exists for
a bill that
probably doesn't have great
prospects in the

24:31.437 --> 24:33.238 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
long run.

24:33.272 --> 24:34.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I personally bet they get
through the House,
just because it's so hard to go
against the

24:34.873 --> 24:37.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sitting president in his first
major thing.

24:37.076 --> 24:39.645 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I wouldn't want to bet on
the eventual
passage of this.

24:39.678 --> 24:42.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Mark, what
we hear is
the main argument they are using
now in the

24:42.214 --> 24:46.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
House as it gets closer to the
vote is the
political vote, you can't go
against your

24:46.452 --> 24:47.419 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
president.

24:47.453 --> 24:49.221 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

24:49.254 --> 24:55.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's an argument that used, used
in 1993 for
the Democrats and Bill Clinton
on his major

24:55.894 --> 25:02.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
budget and tax increase, which,
by the way,
per what David was talking
about, included

25:02.434 --> 25:05.537 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a BTU tax that House members
voted on.

25:05.571 --> 25:11.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It passed the House in a very
difficult vote
and died in the Senate.

25:11.043 --> 25:13.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Several moderate to conservative
Democrats
walked away from it.

25:13.812 --> 25:19.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it left those House members
with a vote
that they really couldn't -- it
became politically

25:19.485 --> 25:22.388 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mortal -- fatal in several
instances.

25:22.421 --> 25:25.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the same thing is true
here, and for
good reasons, Judy.

25:25.824 --> 25:31.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, the Republicans -- part
of David's
answer -- they pledged in 2010,
they pledged

25:31.463 --> 25:34.299 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in 2012, they pledged in 2016.

25:34.333 --> 25:36.969 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That was the one pledge they
had: repeal Obamacare.

25:37.002 --> 25:38.771 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was an applause line.

25:38.804 --> 25:43.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it really did take on almost
a moral imperative,
or at least a political
imperative.

25:43.709 --> 25:48.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, Judy, this is going to
radically overhaul
the Affordable Care Act.

25:48.680 --> 25:50.816 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It going to radically overhaul
Medicaid.

25:50.849 --> 25:54.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You heard Dr. Gurman in his
interview with
Jeff.

25:54.453 --> 25:58.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The reality is, providers are
not going to
provide coverage.

25:58.657 --> 26:03.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're not going to take on as
patients people
under Medicaid, because they are
not going

26:03.362 --> 26:06.064 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to have the money to pay for it.

26:06.098 --> 26:12.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are talking -- one figure
that jumps
out, beyond all the questions of
deductibles

26:12.204 --> 26:19.011 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and everything else, 24 million
Americans.

26:19.044 --> 26:22.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's what the Congressional
Budget Office
estimates.

26:22.347 --> 26:24.583 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And Republicans just kind of
recoiled.

26:24.616 --> 26:27.786 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is the number that has hung
around -- are
going to lose coverage.

26:27.820 --> 26:29.021 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Lose coverage.

26:29.054 --> 26:32.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That just is -- that is truly
unforgivable.

26:32.591 --> 26:34.193 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's morally indefensible.

26:34.226 --> 26:36.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think, in this case, it
will be politically
indefensible.

26:36.361 --> 26:40.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But we're talking
-- you're
talking, Mark, about the bill as
it sits in

26:40.332 --> 26:41.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the House.

26:41.633 --> 26:44.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the Senate, we may -- we're
almost certain
to see changes.

26:44.069 --> 26:46.104 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes, but which
direction?

26:46.138 --> 26:50.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First, on the 24 million, it's a
neat trick
to do that, because simply
repealing Obamacare

26:50.409 --> 26:53.312 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
would have only taken coverage
from 23 million.

26:53.345 --> 26:58.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, somehow, the replacement
subtracts a million,
which is an interesting trick.

26:58.917 --> 27:02.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Republican Party just hasn't
figured out
where it sits on this issue.

27:02.421 --> 27:06.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think you could have a very
good free market
system, sort of modeled on
Switzerland, where

27:06.358 --> 27:10.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there are a lot of individual
markets, people
actually pay for their health
care, and there's

27:10.062 --> 27:14.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some cost and demand -- supply
and demand
pressures to get costs down.

27:14.233 --> 27:17.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you would have to spend more
to get it
-- make it universal.

27:17.035 --> 27:20.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You business have to make it
universal using
a free market system.

27:20.105 --> 27:22.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the Republican Party hasn't
gotten there,
because they don't want to make
it universal,

27:22.708 --> 27:24.810 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because it probably would be
extensive.

27:24.843 --> 27:28.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so some of them want to go
sort of in
that direction, but a lot, Ted
Cruz, Rand

27:28.847 --> 27:31.116 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Paul, they want to go in the
other direction.

27:31.149 --> 27:36.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they just don't think it's
the government's
job to be in the field of
distribution, redistribution.

27:36.522 --> 27:38.824 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And this ACA was very
redistributionist.

27:38.857 --> 27:40.926 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Republican Party hasn't
figured it out.

27:40.959 --> 27:43.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what is interesting to me is
that Donald
Trump hasn't figured it out.

27:43.862 --> 27:45.998 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He campaigned partially as a
populist.

27:46.031 --> 27:50.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if I was a populist, I would
be handing
things to my people.

27:50.035 --> 27:53.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what this bill does is, it
takes things
from the Trump voters.

27:53.605 --> 27:58.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The middle-aged people, 50 to
64, get hammered
in this bill, the people just
above the Medicaid

27:58.477 --> 27:59.444 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
threshold.

27:59.478 --> 28:01.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The working class, they get
hammered.

28:01.313 --> 28:04.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so what is the one piece of
the bill that
has been there from the
beginning to end in

28:04.182 --> 28:08.253 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all the versions, is the tax cut
for people
making over $250,000.

28:08.287 --> 28:13.225 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so it's a weirdly
anti-Trumpian bill that
he has sort of gone along with
because, I

28:13.258 --> 28:15.827 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
guess, the House Republicans led
the way.

28:15.861 --> 28:18.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: I think -- I can't
argue with
any point that David made.

28:18.664 --> 28:21.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I would just say, it's
inconceivable to me.

28:21.466 --> 28:26.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump changed the face of
the Republican
Party, whatever anyone thinks of
this election.

28:26.104 --> 28:30.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He carried 403 counties that had
voted for
Barack Obama.

28:30.409 --> 28:35.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
